{"title_page": "Stutter Rap (No Sleep til Bedtime)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2011}}\n{{More citations needed|date=December 2012}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Stutter Rap (No Sleep til Bedtime)\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Morris Minor and the Majors]]\n| album      =\n| B-side     = Another Boring B-Side\n| released   = 1988\n| format     = [[Gramophone record|7\"]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Comedy rap]]\n| length     =\n| label      = Ten Records Ltd.\n| writer     = [[Tony Hawks]]\n| producer   = [[Grand Master Jelly Tot]] (Jakko Jakszyk)\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = This Is the Chorus\n| next_year  = 1988\n}}\n\n\"'''Stutter Rap (No Sleep til Bedtime)'''\" is a song by [[Morris Minor and the Majors]], led by [[Tony Hawks]]. The song is a stylistic parody of the [[Beastie Boys]], and the subtitle plays on their 1987 single \"[[No Sleep till Brooklyn]]\". The record sold 220,000 copies.\n\nHawks started out as a songwriter but was not successful, and instead became a comedian and writer. However, in turning to comedy he achieved a hit with \"Stutter Rap\", which reached No. 4 in the [[UK Singles Chart]],<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\">{{cite book |first=David |last=Roberts |year=2006 |title=British Hit Singles & Albums |edition=19th |publisher=Guinness World Records Limited  |location=London |isbn=1-904994-10-5 |page=369}}</ref> No. 14 in Canada and No. 2 in Australia. It was written by Hawks, and performed by him along with two others. In the [[music video|video]] for the song, [[John Deacon]] (of [[Queen (band)|Queen]]) makes an appearance, wearing a blue wig and playing guitar.\n\nThe song was [[A-side and B-side|coupled with]] \"Another Boring B-Side\", whose chorus simply repeated the line: \"Very very very very very very boring\".\n\n[[Melody Maker]] reviewed the single with the four words \"Stutter Rap, Utter Crap\".<ref>{{Cite book|ISBN=9780091882082|title=One Hit Wonderland|author=Tony Hawks|page=6}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.tony-hawks.com Tony-Hawks.com (Official website of Tony Hawks)]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1988 singles]]\n[[Category:1988 songs]]\n[[Category:Morris Minor and the Majors songs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2011}}\n{More citations needed|date=December 2012}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Stutter Rap (No Sleep til Bedtime)\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Morris Minor and the Majors]]\n| album      =\n| B-side     = Another Boring B-Side\n| released   = 1988\n| format     = [[Gramophone record|7\"]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Comedy rap]]\n| length     =\n| label      = Ten Records Ltd.\n| writer     = [[Tony Hawks]]\n| producer   = [[Grand Master Jelly Tot]] (Jakko Jakszyk)\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = This Is the Chorus\n| next_year  = 1988\n}}\n\n\"'''Stutter Rap (No Sleep til Bedtime)'''\" is a song by [[Morris Minor and the Majors]], led by [[Tony Hawks]]. The song is a stylistic parody of the [[Beastie Boys]], and the subtitle plays on their 1987 single \"[[No Sleep till Brooklyn]]\". The record sold 220,000 copies.\n\nHawks started out as a songwriter but was not successful, and instead became a comedian and writer. However, in turning to comedy he achieved a hit with \"Stutter Rap\", which reached No. 4 in the [[UK Singles Chart]],<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\">{{cite book |first=David |last=Roberts |year=2006 |title=British Hit Singles & Albums |edition=19th |publisher=Guinness World Records Limited  |location=London |isbn=1-904994-10-5 |page=369}}</ref> No. 14 in Canada and No. 2 in Australia. It was written by Hawks, and performed by him along with two others. In the [[music video|video]] for the song, [[John Deacon]] (of [[Queen (band)|Queen]]) makes an appearance, wearing a blue wig and playing guitar.\n\nThe song was [[A-side and B-side|coupled with]] \"Another Boring B-Side\", whose chorus simply repeated the line: \"Very very very very very very boring\".\n\n[[Melody Maker]] reviewed the single with the four words \"Stutter Rap, Utter Crap\".<ref>{{Cite book|ISBN=9780091882082|title=One Hit Wonderland|author=Tony Hawks|page=6}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.tony-hawks.com Tony-Hawks.com (Official website of Tony Hawks)]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1988 singles]]\n[[Category:1988 songs]]\n[[Category:Morris Minor and the Majors songs]]\n", "name_user": "Redpola", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed unbalanced curly brackets", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stutter_Rap_(No_Sleep_til_Bedtime)"}
{"title_page": "Hugo Speer", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Hugo Speer\n| image        =\n| caption      =\n| birth_name   = Hugo Alexander Speer\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1968|03|17}}\n| birth_place  = [[Harrogate]], [[West Riding of Yorkshire]],<ref>Before 1 April 1974 Harrogate was in the West Riding of Yorkshire.</ref> England\n| spouse       = {{marriage|Vivienne Harvey|19 February 2015}}\n| residence    =\n| occupation   = Actor, director\n| years_active = 1992&ndash;present\n| education    = [[Harrogate Grammar School]]<br/>[[Arts Educational Schools, London|Arts Educational Schools]], London\n}}\n'''Hugo Alexander Speer''' (born 17 March 1968) is an English actor and director.\n\n==Life and career==\nHugo Speer was born in [[Harrogate]] in the [[West Riding of Yorkshire]],<ref>'West Riding of Yorkshire' is correct.</ref><ref name=\"Beacom2001\">\n{{cite news |last=Beacom |first=Brian |title=Star Profile: Hugo Speer |newspaper=[[Evening Times]] |location=Glasgow |date=16 August 2001 |page=21}}</ref> and educated at the local [[Harrogate Grammar School]].<ref name=\"Robinson2009\">{{cite news|last=Robinson|first=Stuart|title=Drink-drive actor Hugo Speer stripped of his driving licence|newspaper=[[Yorkshire Evening Post]]|date=18 July 2009}}</ref> He studied acting at the [[Arts Educational Schools, London]].<ref name=\"Beacom2001\"/>\n\nSpeer began his acting career appearing in the TV series ''[[McCallum (TV series)|McCallum]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hellomagazine.com/profiles/hugo-speer/|title=Hugo Speer |work=[[Hello!]]|accessdate=26 May 2016}}</ref> ''[[The Bill]]'',<ref name=\"Beacom2001\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.buddytv.com/info/hugo-speer-info.aspx |title=Hugo Speer Biography |publisher=[[BuddyTV]] |accessdate=26 May 2016}}</ref> and ''[[Heartbeat (UK TV series)|Heartbeat]]''. He played a minor role in the film ''[[Bhaji on the Beach]]'' before his first notable appearance as Guy in the film ''[[The Full Monty]]''.<ref name=\"Beacom2001\"/> Following this film's worldwide success he went on to appear in ''Swing'' (1999), ''[[Deathwatch (2002 film)|Deathwatch]]'' and ''[[The Interpreter]]'' (playing [[Nicole Kidman]]'s brother). However, most of his work has been on TV, including sitcom ''[[Men Behaving Badly]]'', dramas ''[[Clocking Off]]'', ''[[The Last Detective]]'', ''[[Boudica (film)|Boudica]]'' (2003), and ''[[The Rotters' Club (book)|The Rotters' Club]]'' (2005), as well as the 2005 [[BBC]] adaptation of [[Charles Dickens|Dickens']] ''[[Bleak House (2005 TV serial)|Bleak House]]''. In 2006, he appeared in the postal worker drama ''[[Sorted (TV series)|Sorted]]''. In 2008, he starred alongside [[Martine McCutcheon]] in ''[[Echo Beach (TV series)|Echo Beach]]''. In 2011 he played a repairman whose repairs \"come to life\" in the supernatural drama ''[[Haven (TV series)|Haven]]'', based on a [[Stephen King]] story. Speer also provides narration for [[ITV1]] series, ''Cops with Cameras'', [[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]]'s ''[[The Bachelor (UK TV series)|The Bachelor]]'', [[Channel 4]] series ''[[999: What's Your Emergency?]]'' and the [[BBC]] series ''Seaside Rescue''.\nHe appears as John Foster in the penultimate and final episodes of the fourth series of ''[[Skins (UK TV series)|Skins]]''.\n\nIn 2002 he starred as Sergeant David Tate in the film ''[[Deathwatch (2002 film)|Deathwatch]]'', a [[2002 film|2002]] European [[horror film]] directed by [[Michael J. Bassett]].\n\nHugo Speer also narrated a factual programme on [[Discovery HD]] called ''Gold Divers'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.discoveryuk.com/shows/gold-divers/ |title=Gold Divers |work=Discovery UK |accessdate=26 May 2016}}</ref> and [[Alaska: The Last Frontier]]. \n\nSince 2010 he has played the lead character of DCI John Stone in eight series of the [[BBC Radio 4]] police drama ''Stone''.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b09m370r|title = Stone|publisher = BBC Radio 4|accessdate = 10 January 2019}}</ref> From 2013 to 2014 he starred as Inspector Valentine in the new version of ''[[Father Brown (2013 TV series)|Father Brown]]'' on [[BBC]] TV in the first series and the first episode of the second series. He made a return appearance in the 2020 episode 8.10 \"The Tower of Lost Souls\"\n\nStarting in 2014, Speer starred as [[Comte de Troisville|Captain Treville]] in ''[[The Musketeers]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/mediapacks/musketeers/hugo-speer |title=Interview with Hugo Speer |work=BBC Media Centre |accessdate=26 May 2016}}</ref> The series ended in 2016.\n\n==Director==\nIn 2010 Hugo Speer made his directorial d\u00e9but with the short film ''[[Mam (film)|MAM]]'' starring [[Josie Lawrence]], [[Paul Barber (actor)|Paul Barber]] and Ronan Carter. The family drama about a 12-year-old boy was scripted by Vivienne Harvey. It was produced by Vigo Films and shot mostly in [[Sheffield]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1730304/ |title=Mam (2010) |date=1 November 2010 |publisher=IMDb |accessdate=26 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nOn 19 February 2015, Speer married [[Glasgow|Glaswegian]] actress, writer and director Vivienne Harvey.\n\nIn 2009, Speer was involved in a car accident that saw him crash his BMW into a traffic island while driving after drinking over the legal limit. He was returning from a wake. No one was hurt in the incident and Speer was banned from driving for eighteen months.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1200403/Full-Monty-actor-Hugo-Speer-banned-roads-drink-driving-home-friends-wake.html |title=Full Monty actor Hugo Speer banned from the roads for drink driving home from friend's wake |date=17 July 2009 |work=[[Daily Mail]] |accessdate=26 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nSpeer moved to London after his success in ''[[The Full Monty]]'' and lived there for fifteen years but moved back to his native North Yorkshire. His pastimes include falconry, walking and music. He is a supporter of [[Leeds United]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2005/08_august/18/messiah_speer.shtml |title=Messiah series four press pack Hugo Speer |date=8 August 2005|work=BBC Press Office |accessdate=26 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe is friends with fellow actor [[Andrew Scarborough]], whom he worked with in the ''[[Hearts and Bones (TV series)|Hearts and Bones]]'' for two series. Speer and Scarborough have known each other since they were children.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-76672961.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201032737/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-76672961.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=1 December 2017 |title=Andy Gets a Kick out of Life; Acting Is Simply Child's Play for Andrew Scarborough after Renewing an Old Pals Act in Top BBC Drama Hearts and Bones |newspaper=[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]] |location=Glasgow |date=21 July 2001 |publisher=[[HighBeam Research]] |accessdate=26 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0817563|Hugo Speer}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Speer, Hugo}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:People educated at the Arts Educational Schools]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Outstanding Performance by a Cast in a Motion Picture Screen Actors Guild Award winners]]\n[[Category:Actors from Harrogate]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:English male radio actors]]\n[[Category:English film directors]]\n[[Category:20th-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century English male actors]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Hugo Speer\n| image        =\n| caption      =\n| birth_name   = Hugo Alexander Speer\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1968|03|17}}\n| birth_place  = [[Harrogate]], [[West Riding of Yorkshire]],<ref>Before 1 April 1974 Harrogate was in the West Riding of Yorkshire.</ref> England\n| spouse       = {{marriage|Vivienne Harvey|19 February 2015}}\n| residence    =\n| occupation   = Actor, director\n| years_active = 1992&ndash;present\n| education    = [[Harrogate Grammar School]]<br/>[[Arts Educational Schools, London|Arts Educational Schools]], London\n}}\n'''Hugo Alexander Speer''' (born 17 March 1968) is an English actor and director.\n\n==Life and career==\nHugo Speer was born in [[Harrogate]] in the [[West Riding of Yorkshire]],<ref>'West Riding of Yorkshire' is correct.</ref><ref name=\"Beacom2001\">\n{{cite news |last=Beacom |first=Brian |title=Star Profile: Hugo Speer |newspaper=[[Evening Times]] |location=Glasgow |date=16 August 2001 |page=21}}</ref> and educated at the local [[Harrogate Grammar School]].<ref name=\"Robinson2009\">{{cite news |last=Robinson |first=Stuart |title=Drink-drive actor Hugo Speer stripped of his driving licence |newspaper=[[Yorkshire Evening Post]] |date=18 July 2009}}</ref> He studied acting at the [[Arts Educational Schools, London]].<ref name=\"Beacom2001\"/>\n\nSpeer began his acting career appearing in the TV series ''[[McCallum (TV series)|McCallum]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hellomagazine.com/profiles/hugo-speer/ |title=Hugo Speer |work=[[Hello!]] |accessdate=26 May 2016}}</ref> ''[[The Bill]]''<ref name=\"Beacom2001\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.buddytv.com/info/hugo-speer-info.aspx |title=Hugo Speer Biography |publisher=[[BuddyTV]] |accessdate=26 May 2016}}</ref> and ''[[Heartbeat (UK TV series)|Heartbeat]]''. He played a minor role in the film ''[[Bhaji on the Beach]]'' before his first notable appearance as Guy in the film ''[[The Full Monty]]''.<ref name=\"Beacom2001\"/> Following this film's worldwide success he went on to appear in ''Swing'' (1999), ''[[Deathwatch (2002 film)|Deathwatch]]'' and ''[[The Interpreter]]'' (playing [[Nicole Kidman]]'s brother). However, most of his work has been on TV, including sitcom ''[[Men Behaving Badly]]'', dramas ''[[Clocking Off]]'', ''[[The Last Detective]]'', ''[[Boudica (film)|Boudica]]'' (2003), and ''[[The Rotters' Club (book)|The Rotters' Club]]'' (2005), as well as the 2005 [[BBC]] adaptation of [[Charles Dickens|Dickens']] ''[[Bleak House (2005 TV serial)|Bleak House]]''. In 2006, he appeared in the postal worker drama ''[[Sorted (TV series)|Sorted]]''. In 2008, he starred alongside [[Martine McCutcheon]] in ''[[Echo Beach (TV series)|Echo Beach]]''. In 2011 he played a repairman whose repairs \"come to life\" in the supernatural drama ''[[Haven (TV series)|Haven]]'', based on a [[Stephen King]] story. Speer also provides narration for [[ITV1]] series, ''Cops with Cameras'', [[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]]'s ''[[The Bachelor (UK TV series)|The Bachelor]]'', [[Channel 4]] series ''[[999: What's Your Emergency?]]'' and the [[BBC]] series ''Seaside Rescue''.\nHe appears as John Foster in the penultimate and final episodes of the fourth series of ''[[Skins (UK TV series)|Skins]]''.\n\nIn 2002 he starred as Sergeant David Tate in the film ''[[Deathwatch (2002 film)|Deathwatch]]'', a [[2002 film|2002]] European [[horror film]] directed by [[Michael J. Bassett]].\n\nHugo Speer also narrated a factual programme on [[Discovery HD]] called ''Gold Divers''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.discoveryuk.com/shows/gold-divers/ |title=Gold Divers |work=Discovery UK |accessdate=26 May 2016}}</ref> and [[Alaska: The Last Frontier]]. \n\nSince 2010 he has played the lead character of DCI John Stone in eight series of the [[BBC Radio 4]] police drama ''Stone''.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b09m370r|title = Stone|publisher = BBC Radio 4|accessdate = 10 January 2019}}</ref> From 2013 to 2014 he starred as Inspector Valentine in the new version of ''[[Father Brown (2013 TV series)|Father Brown]]'' on [[BBC]] TV in the first series and the first episode of the second series. He made a return appearance in the 2020 episode 8.10 \"The Tower of Lost Souls\"\n\nStarting in 2014, Speer starred as [[Comte de Troisville|Captain Treville]] in ''[[The Musketeers]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/mediapacks/musketeers/hugo-speer |title=Interview with Hugo Speer |work=BBC Media Centre |accessdate=26 May 2016}}</ref> The series ended in 2016.\n\n==Director==\nIn 2010 Hugo Speer made his directorial d\u00e9but with the short film ''[[Mam (film)|MAM]]'' starring [[Josie Lawrence]], [[Paul Barber (actor)|Paul Barber]] and Ronan Carter. The family drama about a 12-year-old boy was scripted by Vivienne Harvey. It was produced by Vigo Films and shot mostly in [[Sheffield]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1730304/ |title=Mam (2010) |date=1 November 2010 |publisher=IMDb |accessdate=26 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nOn 19 February 2015, Speer married [[Glasgow|Glaswegian]] actress, writer and director Vivienne Harvey.\n\nIn 2009, Speer was involved in a car accident that saw him crash his BMW into a traffic island while driving after drinking over the legal limit. He was returning from a wake. No one was hurt in the incident and Speer was banned from driving for eighteen months.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1200403/Full-Monty-actor-Hugo-Speer-banned-roads-drink-driving-home-friends-wake.html |title=Full Monty actor Hugo Speer banned from the roads for drink driving home from friend's wake |date=17 July 2009 |work=[[Daily Mail]] |accessdate=26 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nSpeer moved to London after his success in ''[[The Full Monty]]'' and lived there for fifteen years but moved back to his native North Yorkshire. His pastimes include falconry, walking and music. He is a supporter of [[Leeds United]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2005/08_august/18/messiah_speer.shtml |title=Messiah series four press pack Hugo Speer |date=8 August 2005|work=BBC Press Office |accessdate=26 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe is friends with fellow actor [[Andrew Scarborough]], whom he worked with in the ''[[Hearts and Bones (TV series)|Hearts and Bones]]'' for two series. Speer and Scarborough have known each other since they were children.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-76672961.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201032737/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-76672961.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=1 December 2017 |title=Andy Gets a Kick out of Life; Acting Is Simply Child's Play for Andrew Scarborough after Renewing an Old Pals Act in Top BBC Drama Hearts and Bones |newspaper=[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]] |location=Glasgow |date=21 July 2001 |publisher=[[HighBeam Research]] |accessdate=26 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n== References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0817563|Hugo Speer}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Speer, Hugo}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:People educated at the Arts Educational Schools]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Outstanding Performance by a Cast in a Motion Picture Screen Actors Guild Award winners]]\n[[Category:Actors from Harrogate]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:English male radio actors]]\n[[Category:English film directors]]\n[[Category:20th-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century English male actors]]\n", "name_user": "Indoreli", "label": "safe", "comment": "Clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hugo_Speer"}
{"title_page": "Brasil Online", "text_new": "{{Infobox company \n| name = Brasil Online\n| logo = \n| foundation = 1996\n| caption= \n| location = [[Brasil]]\n| key_people = \n| industry = Internet\n| products = Site\n| revenue = \n| operating_income = Brasil Online\n| net_income = \n| num_employees = \n| parent = \n| homepage = {{URL|https://www.bol.com.br}}\n}}\n\n'''Brasil Online (BOL)''' is an internet portal that provides email hosting and free email services [[Universo Online|UOL]].\n\n==History==\n\nIn April 1996, BOL was launched in Brazil by [[Grupo Abril]], one of the largest Communication Holdings in Brazil.<ref name=\"Noticias\">{{cite news|url=http://www.abril.com.br/institucional/50anos/internet.html|title=Da visita \u00e0s bancas \u00e0 viagem na rede|publisher=[[Abril]]|accessdate=August 25, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130407034021/http://www.abril.com.br/institucional/50anos/internet.html|archive-date=April 7, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\nGrupo Abril and [[Grupo Folha]], which owns (UOL), signed a joint-venture that September. UOL acquired BOL and created the largest Brazilian internet provider in numbers of subscribers and amount of content in Portuguese.<ref name=\"Mercado\">{{cite news|url=http://www.istoedinheiro.com.br/noticias/mercado-digital/20010825/golpe-preco/23922.shtml|title=Golpe de pre\u00e7o| publisher=[[Isto \u00e9 Dinheiro]]|accessdate=August 25, 2014}}</ref> Features such as news, photos, videos, chat rooms and entertainment are offered by the portal. It has million users every month.\nIn October 1999, BOL was re-branded as the first free email provider in Brazil. BOL hosted more than million email accounts by the following August.<ref name=\"Arquivo\">{{cite news|url=http://www.estadao.com.br/arquivo/tecnologia/2000/not20000808p12653.htm|title=Bol diz ter milh\u00f5es de assinantes| newspaper=[[Estad\u00e3o]]|accessdate=August 25, 2014}}</ref>\nBOL launched a new email platform based in [[AJAX (programming)|AJAX]] with [[Web 2.0]] technology in 2008. The platform has search engines that go through each folder as well as provide automatic contact storage, create filters to organize messages, including smart visualization of attached files and creating contact groups.<ref>{{cite web|title=A Beginner's Guide to Successful Email Marketing|url=https://www.gmailfaxpro.com/tutorials/how-to-send-a-fax-from-gmail/|publisher=Shirley R. Sanders|accessdate=13 September 2014}}</ref>\n[[File:Button-BOL-1995.jpg|thumb|''Button'' promocional do Brasil Online, criado em 1996 com logomarca concebida pelo tip\u00f3grafo e designer Tony de Marco]]\nIn 2011, BOL partnered with sports journalist Milton Neves. With the partnership, Neves hosted his sports portal \"Terceiro Tempo\" and blog covering news, opinions and Brazilian and International football side stories on BOL.<ref name=\"Midia\">{{cite news|url=http://www.adnews.com.br/midia/bol-anuncia-parceria-com-milton-neves\n|title=BOL anuncia parceria com Milton Neves| publisher=[[Adnews]]|accessdate=August 25, 2014}}</ref>\nIn 2013, BOL partnered with Elancers to create a resume database on the BOL Empregos page. BOL Empregos is a free service that gathers more than 40,000 jobs for meeting from over 6,000 business for sale. A new version of the BOL mobile mail app for [[Smartphones]] and [[Tablet computer|Tablets]] compatible with [[Android (operating system)|Android]] and [[iOS]] operating systems was released that year.<ref name=\"Not\u00edcias\">{{cite news|url=http://www.abrhnacional.org.br/noticias/1731-bol-e-elancers-estreiam-o-banco-de-curriculos-bol-empregos.html|title=BOL e Elancers estreiam o banco de curr\u00edculos BOL Empregos|publisher=[[ABRH]]|accessdate=August 25, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140821212910/http://www.abrhnacional.org.br/noticias/1731-bol-e-elancers-estreiam-o-banco-de-curriculos-bol-empregos.html|archive-date=August 21, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Services==\n\n===BOL Mail===\nBOL offers a free email service with a 6 GB capacity, spellchecker, customizable themes and interfaces for [[iPhone]], [[iPad]] and [[Android (operating system)|Android]]. Since 2012, BOL uses the IMAP system for send and receive procedures to ensure that the original server\u2019s content is not erased.<ref name=\"Tecnologia\">{{cite news|url=http://www.baguete.com.br/noticias/internet/04/08/2008/uol-e-mail-baseado-em-ajax|title=UOL: email baseado| publisher=[[Baguete]]|accessdate=August 25, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===BOL Not\u00edcias===\nThe BOL Not\u00edcias platform has more than 100 million page views every month. The portal offers sports, entertainment and cooking content in real time. It also reproduces news from sources such as UOL, national and international news agencies.\n\n===BOL Chat===\nBOL\u2019s [[Online chat|chat]] is free and accessible to the general public. BOL Chat offers more than 700 chat rooms, 9 themes and has approximately 70 million page views every month.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://bpbol.uol.com.br/#rmcl|title=BOL email gr\u00e1tis do Brasil| publisher=[[Bate Papo]]|accessdate=May 15, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==VilaBOL==\n\nVilaBOL was a free cloud data hosting service provided by BOL. VilaBOL offered 15 MB of storage, an e-mail account, a web designer tool, a poll designer and a hit counter for each user. The service was terminated in 2012.<ref name=\"Home\">{{cite news|url=http://vila.bol.uol.com.br/|title=O servi\u00e7o de hospedagem de sites VilaBOL foi desativado| publisher=[[Universo Online|UOL]]|accessdate=August 25, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://www.uol.com.br}}\n\n[[Category:Grupo Folha]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 1996]]\n[[Category:Brazilian websites]]\n[[Category:Internet service providers of Brazil]]\n[[Category:Free email hosting]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company \n| name = Brasil Online\n| logo = \n| foundation = 1996\n| caption= \n| location = [[Brasil]]\n| key_people = \n| industry = Internet\n| products = Site\n| revenue = \n| operating_income = Brasil Online\n| net_income = \n| num_employees = \n| parent = \n| homepage = {{URL|https://www.bol.com.br}}\n}}\n\n'''Brasil Online (BOL)''' is an internet portal that provides email hosting and free email services [[Universo Online|UOL]].\n\n==History==\n\nIn April 1996, BOL was launched in Brazil by [[Grupo Abril]], one of the largest Communication Holdings in Brazil.<ref name=\"Noticias\">{{cite news|url=http://www.abril.com.br/institucional/50anos/internet.html|title=Da visita \u00e0s bancas \u00e0 viagem na rede|publisher=[[Abril]]|accessdate=August 25, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130407034021/http://www.abril.com.br/institucional/50anos/internet.html|archive-date=April 7, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\nGrupo Abril and [[Grupo Folha]], which owns (UOL), signed a joint-venture that September. UOL acquired BOL and created the largest Brazilian internet provider in numbers of subscribers and amount of content in Portuguese.<ref name=\"Mercado\">{{cite news|url=http://www.istoedinheiro.com.br/noticias/mercado-digital/20010825/golpe-preco/23922.shtml|title=Golpe de pre\u00e7o| publisher=[[Isto \u00e9 Dinheiro]]|accessdate=August 25, 2014}}</ref> Features such as news, photos, videos, chat rooms and entertainment are offered by the portal. It has million users every month.\nIn October 1999, BOL was re-branded as the first free email provider in Brazil. BOL hosted more than million email accounts by the following August.<ref name=\"Arquivo\">{{cite news|url=http://www.estadao.com.br/arquivo/tecnologia/2000/not20000808p12653.htm|title=Bol diz ter milh\u00f5es de assinantes| newspaper=[[Estad\u00e3o]]|accessdate=August 25, 2014}}</ref>\nBOL launched a new email platform based in [[AJAX (programming)|AJAX]] with [[Web 2.0]] technology in 2008. The platform has search engines that go through each folder as well as provide automatic contact storage, create filters to organize messages, including smart visualization of attached files and creating contact groups.<ref>{{cite web|title=A Beginner's Guide to Successful Email Marketing|url=https://www.gmailfaxpro.com/tutorials/how-to-send-a-fax-from-gmail/|publisher=Shirley R. Sanders|accessdate=13 September 2014}}</ref>\n[[File:Button-BOL-1995.jpg|thumb|''Button'' promocional do Brasil Online, criado em 1996 com logomarca concebida pelo tip\u00f3grafo e designer Tony de Marco]]\nIn 2011, BOL partnered with sports journalist Milton Neves. With the partnership, Neves hosted his sports portal \"Terceiro Tempo\" and blog covering news, opinions and Brazilian and International football side stories on BOL.<ref name=\"Midia\">{{cite news|url=http://www.adnews.com.br/midia/bol-anuncia-parceria-com-milton-neves\n|title=BOL anuncia parceria com Milton Neves| publisher=[[Adnews]]|accessdate=August 25, 2014}}</ref>\nIn 2013, BOL partnered with Elancers to create a resume database on the BOL Empregos page. BOL Empregos is a free service that gathers more than 40,000 jobs for meeting from over 6,000 business for sale. A new version of the BOL mobile mail app for [[Smartphones]] and [[Tablet computer|Tablets]] compatible with [[Android (operating system)|Android]] and [[iOS]] operating systems was released that year.<ref name=\"Not\u00edcias\">{{cite news|url=http://www.abrhnacional.org.br/noticias/1731-bol-e-elancers-estreiam-o-banco-de-curriculos-bol-empregos.html|title=BOL e Elancers estreiam o banco de curr\u00edculos BOL Empregos|publisher=[[ABRH]]|accessdate=August 25, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140821212910/http://www.abrhnacional.org.br/noticias/1731-bol-e-elancers-estreiam-o-banco-de-curriculos-bol-empregos.html|archive-date=August 21, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Services==\n\n===BOL Mail===\nBOL offers a free email service with a 6 GB capacity, spellchecker, customizable themes and interfaces for [[iPhone]], [[iPad]] and [[Android (operating system)|Android]]. Since 2012, BOL uses the IMAP system for send and receive procedures to ensure that the original server\u2019s content is not erased.<ref name=\"Tecnologia\">{{cite news|url=http://www.baguete.com.br/noticias/internet/04/08/2008/uol-e-mail-baseado-em-ajax|title=UOL: email baseado| publisher=[[Baguete]]|accessdate=August 25, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===BOL Not\u00edcias===\nThe BOL Not\u00edcias platform has more than 100 million page views every month. The portal offers sports, entertainment and cooking content in real time. It also reproduces news from sources such as UOL, national and international news agencies.\n\n===BOL Chat===\nBOL\u2019s [[Online chat|chat]] is free and accessible to the general public. BOL Chat offers more than 700 chat rooms, 9 themes and has approximately 70 million page views every month.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://bpbol.uol.com.br/#rmcl|title=BOL email gr\u00e1tis do Brasil| publisher=[[Bate Papo]]|accessdate=May 15, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==VilaBOL==\n\nVilaBOL was a free cloud data hosting service provided by BOL. VilaBOL offered 15 MB of storage, an e-mail account, a web designer tool, a poll designer and a hit counter for each user. The service was terminated in 2012.<ref name=\"Home\">{{cite news|url=http://vila.bol.uol.com.br/|title=O servi\u00e7o de hospedagem de sites VilaBOL foi desativado| publisher=[[Universo Online|UOL]]|accessdate=August 25, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{official website|http://www.uol.com.br}}\n\n[[Category:Grupo Folha]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 1996]]\n[[Category:Brazilian websites]]\n[[Category:Internet service providers of Brazil]]\n[[Category:Free email hosting]]\n", "name_user": "Nemo bis", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:Bullet.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brasil_Online"}
{"title_page": "GM High Feature engine", "text_new": "{{Infobox automobile engine\n| name          = [[File:General Motors logo.svg|25px]] High Feature V6\n| image         = Alloytec V6 (LPG) engine of a 2006-2008 Holden VE Commodore 1.jpg\n| caption       = Alloytec LPG V6 engine in a 2006-2008 [[Holden VE Commodore]]\n| manufacturer  = [[General Motors]]\n| aka           = Alloytec V6\n| production    = 2004-present\n| predecessor   ={{ubl |[[Buick V6 engine]]|[[GM 54-Degree V6 engine|54\u00b0 V6]]|[[GM High Value engine]]|[[Northstar engine series#LX5 (Shortstar)|LX5 (Shortstar)]]}}\n| configuration = 60\u00b0 [[V6 engine|V6]]\n| block         = [[Aluminum]]\n| head          = Aluminum\n| valvetrain    = [[Dual overhead cam|DOHC]] [[Multi-valve#Four valves|4 valves x cyl.]] with [[Variable valve timing|VVT]]\n| fuelsystem    = [[Sequential multi-port fuel injection]]<br>[[Gasoline direct injection|Direct injection]]\n| fueltype      = [[Gasoline]], [[E85]], [[Autogas|LPG]]\n| oilsystem     = [[Wet sump]]\n| coolingsystem = [[Radiator (engine cooling)|Water-cooled]]\n| turbocharger  = [[Twin-turbo]] (in some models)\n| compression   = 9.5:1, 10.0:1, 10.2:1, 10.3:1, 11.3:1, 11.5:1, 11.7:1, 12.2:1\n| displacement  = {{Unbulleted list|{{convert|2792|cc|L|abbr=on}}|{{convert|2994|cc|L|abbr=on}}|{{convert|3195|cc|L|abbr=on}}|{{convert|3564|cc|L|abbr=on}}|{{convert|3649|cc|L|abbr=on}}}}\n| bore          = {{Unbulleted list|{{convert|86|mm|in|2|abbr=on}}|{{convert|89|mm|in|abbr=on}}|{{convert|94|mm|in|abbr=on}}|{{convert|95|mm|in|2|abbr=on}}}}\n| stroke        = {{Unbulleted list|{{convert|74.8|mm|in|2|abbr=on}}|{{convert|80.3|mm|in|2|abbr=on}}|{{convert|85.6|mm|in|2|abbr=on}}|{{convert|85.8|mm|in|2|abbr=on}}}}\n| redline       = 6500-7200\n| emissions level = [[Euro 6]]\n| power         = {{Convert|201-464|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}}\n| torque        = {{convert|182-445|lbft|Nm|0|abbr=on}}\n}}\nThe '''GM High Feature engine''' (also known as the '''HFV6''', and including the '''3600 LY7''' and derivative '''LP1''') is a family of modern [[General Motors Corporation|General Motors]] [[DOHC]] [[V6 engine]]s. The series was introduced in 2004 with the [[Cadillac CTS]] and the [[Holden Commodore (VZ)]].\n\nIt is a 60\u00b0 24-valve design with aluminum block and heads and [[Sequential multi-port fuel injection]]. Most versions feature [[Continuous variable valve timing|continuously variable cam phasing]] on both intake and exhaust valves and [[electronic throttle control]]. Other features include piston oil-jet capability, forged and [[Deep Rolling|fillet rolled]] [[crankshaft]], sinter forged [[connecting rod]]s, a [[VLIM|variable-length intake manifold]], twin knock control sensors and [[Direct Ignition#Direct ignition|coil-on-plug ignition]]. It was developed by the same international team responsible for the [[GM Ecotec engine#Ecotec|Ecotec]], including the [[Opel]] engineers responsible for the [[GM 54-Degree V6 engine|54\u00b0 V6]], with involvement with design and development engineering from [[Ricardo plc]].\n\n[[Holden]] sells the HFV6 under the name '''Alloytec'''. The '''High Feature''' moniker on the Holden produced engine is reserved for the twin cam phasing high output version. The block was designed to be expandable from 2.8&nbsp;L to 4.0&nbsp;L. High Feature V6 engines were previously produced in Fishermans Bend, [[Port Melbourne]], [[Australia]] and remain in production at the following four manufacturing locations: [[St. Catharines]], [[Canada]]; [[Flint Engine South]] in [[Flint, Michigan]], [[United States]]; Romulus Engine Plant in Romulus, MI and [[Ramos Arizpe Assembly|Ramos Arizpe, Coahuila, Mexico]]. The assembly lines for the St. Catharines and Flint facilities were manufactured by Hirata Corporation at their powertrain facility in [[Kumamoto, Japan]]. Most of the designs of this motor happened in Flint. They were first produced for the Cadillac range.\n\n== History ==\nThe HFV6 was first designed, tested and produced in a joint program by [[Cadillac]] and Holden. A majority of designs into the new alloy construction, transmission pairing and first use in production were all undertaken in Detroit (and manufactured in [[St. Catharines, Ontario]]). Holden had the job of developing smaller engines (Holden 3.2, LP1 and Saab 2.8, LP9 Turbo) as well as their own Holden 3.6 HFV6 (called the Alloytec V6) for local models.\n\nCadillac and Holden both tested variations of these engines in US and Australia.\n\n== 2.8 ==\n\n=== LP1 ===\nA {{convert|2792|cc|L|1|order=flip|abbr=on}} ''LP1'' variant was introduced in the 2005 [[Cadillac CTS]]. It was also used on the Chinese 2008 CTS. It has a {{convert|89x74.8|mm|in|2|abbr=on}} bore and stroke, [[Sequential multi-port fuel injection]] and a 10.0:1 compression ratio. The ''LP1'' was built in St. Catharines, Ontario.\n\nApplications:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year(s)\n! Model\n! Power\n! Torque\n|-\n| 2007\u20132009\n| [[Buick Park Avenue#Third generation (2007\u20132012)|Buick Park Avenue]] (China)\n| {{Convert|201|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} @ 6500 rpm\n| {{convert|195|lbft|Nm|0|abbr=on}} @ 2600 rpm\n|-\n| 2005\u20132007\n| [[Cadillac CTS#First generation (2003\u20132007)|Cadillac CTS]]\n| {{Convert|210|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} @ 6500 rpm\n| {{convert|194|lbft|Nm|0|abbr=on}} @ 3300 rpm\n|-\n|2008-2010\n| [[Cadillac CTS#Second generation (2008-2014)|Cadillac CTS]]\n| {{convert|210|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} @ 6800 rpm\n| {{convert|182|lbft|Nm|0|abbr=on}} @ 3600 rpm\n|-\n| 2007\u20132009\n| [[Cadillac STS|Cadillac SLS]] (China)\n| {{Convert|209|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} @ 6500 rpm\n| {{convert|194|lbft|Nm|0|abbr=on}} @ 3300 rpm\n|}\n\n=== LP9 {{Anchor|A28NET|Z28NET|B284}} ===\n[[File:2006 Saab 9-3 SportCombi engine.jpg|right|thumb|250px|2.8&nbsp;L turbo V6 in a 2006 [[Saab 9-3]]]]\n\n''This engine is also known as a A28NET, Z28NET, Z28NEL or B284.''\n\nThe ''LP9'' is a 2.8&nbsp;L [[Turbocharger|turbocharged]] version used for the [[Saab 9-3]], [[Saab 9-5]] and other GM vehicles. It has the same bore and stroke as the [[naturally aspirated]] [[GM High Feature engine#LP1|LP1]], however the compression ratio is reduced to 9.5:1. The engine is manufactured at Holden's Fishermans Bend engine factory in Port Melbourne, Australia, while GM Powertrain Sweden (formerly Saab Automobile Powertrain) is responsible for turbocharging the engine. Global versions of this engine use the same horsepower rating for both metric and imperial markets \u2013 [[Horsepower#Mechanical horsepower|mechanical horsepower]] \u2013 while the Europe-only versions are rated in [[Horsepower#Metric horsepower|metric horsepower]].\n\nApplications:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year(s)\n! Model\n! Power\n! Torque\n|-\n| 2005-2008\n| [[Opel Vectra#Vectra C (2002\u20132008)|Opel Vectra]] / [[Vauxhall Vectra]]\n| {{Convert|230|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} @ 5500 rpm\n| {{Convert|330|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} @ 1900-4500 rpm\n|-\n| 2005-2008\n| [[Opel Signum]] \n| {{Convert|230|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} @ 5500 rpm\n|{{Convert|330|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} @ 1900-4500 rpm\n|-\n|2006\u20132008\n|[[Opel Signum]]\n|{{Convert|247|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} @ 5500 rpm\n|{{Convert|350|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} @ 1900-4500 rpm\n|-\n| 2005\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Opel Vectra#Vectra C (2002\u20132008)|Opel Vectra OPC]] \n| {{Convert|247|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} @ 5500 rpm\n| {{Convert|350|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} @ 1900-4500 rpm\n|-\n| 2006\u20132008\n| {{Convert|276|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} @ 5500 rpm\n|{{Convert|350|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} @ 1900-4500 rpm\n|-\n| 2006\u20132009\n| [[Cadillac BLS]]\n| {{Convert|250|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} @ 5500 rpm\n|{{Convert|350|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} @ 1900-4500 rpm\n|-\n| 2006\u20132008\n| rowspan= \"2\" | [[Saab 9-3#Second generation (2003-2007) and second generation facelift (2008-present)|Saab 9-3]] Aero\n| {{Convert|250|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} @ 5500 rpm\n|{{Convert|350|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} @ 1900-4500 rpm\n|-\n| 2009\n| {{Convert|280|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} @ 5500 rpm\n| {{Convert|400|Nm|lbft|0|